                    <h2>What is Spear-Phishing?</h2>
                    <p>
                        Spear-phishing is a highly targeted form of phishing in which attackers impersonate a trusted source to deceive individuals into revealing sensitive information, such as passwords, financial data, or personal details. 
                        Unlike traditional phishing, which sends mass emails, spear-phishing is customized for a specific individual or organization, making it more convincing and dangerous.
                    </p>
                    <h2>How Spear-Phishing Works</h2>
                    <h3>Spear-phishing attacks typically follow these steps:</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>Research & Reconnaissance:</b> Attackers gather personal details from social media, company websites, and public records.</li>
                        <li><b>Crafting the Attack:</b> A customized email or message is created to appear as if it is from a known and trusted entity.</li>
                        <li><b>Delivery & Deception:</b> The target receives an email or message with an urgent request to click a link, open an attachment, or provide sensitive information.</li>
                        <li><b>Exploitation & Data Theft:</b> The victim’s information is stolen, malware is installed, or credentials are used to gain unauthorized access.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h2>Common Tactics Used in Spear-Phishing</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>Impersonation:</b> Attackers pose as a coworker, executive or vender.</li>
                        <li><b>Urgency & Fear:</b> Messages pressure recipients to act quickly.</li>
                        <li><b>Fake Links & Attachments:</b> Links lead to fraudulent login pages; attachments contain malware.</li>
                        <li><b>Personalized Content:</b> Emails reference specific projects, colleagues, or events to seem legitimate.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h2>Hold to Identify  Spear-Phising Attempt</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Unusual sender email addresses or domains.</li>
                        <li>Requests for sensitive information.</li>
                        <li>Urgent or threatening language urging immediate action.</li>
                        <li>Suspicious links-hover over them to check the actual destination.</li>
                        <li>Unexpected attachments from unkown senders.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h2>How to Protect Yourself</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>Verify Requests:</b> Contact the sender directly using a trusted method before sharing any information.</li>
                        <li><b>Enable Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA):</b> Adds an extra layer of security to your accounts.</li>
                        <li><b>Use Strong Unique Passwords:</b> Consider using a password manager, such as Microsoft Authenticator, Google Authenticator, etc.</li>
                        <li><b>Keep Software Updated:</b> Ensure that your operating system, browser, and security software are up to date.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h2>What to Do if You Suspect a Spear-Phishing Attack</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <li><b>Do Not Click or Respond:</b> Avoid interacting with the email or message</li>
                        <li><b>Report It:</b> Forward phishing emails to reportphishing@apwg.org</li>
                        <li><b>Change Compromised Credentials:</b> Update passwords immediately if you suspect exposure.</li>
                        <li><b>Monitor Accounts for Suspicious Activity:</b> Check for unauthorized logins or transactions.</li>
                    </ul>
